"""
MKT Original Language Commentary — Ephesians chapters 1–4
Run: python3 scripts/zc-original-ephesians-1-4.py

Source data used:
- data/interlinear/ephesians.json
- data/translation/glossary-greek.json (σάρξ dl=4, νεκρός dl=2)
- data/translation/draft/mediating/ephesians.json (MKT text for quoting)
- data/commentary/ellicott/ephesians.json (philological references)

Key decisions in this range:
- σάρξ (G4561) at 2:3 and throughout: dispute_level=4; treated as "the creaturely human
  nature in its frailty and sinful inclination," not as body/meat. Context governs.
- 1:23 πλήρωμα: the active-participle phrase τοῦ τὰ πάντα ἐν πᾶσιν πληρουμένου renders
  Christ as the one doing the filling, not as being filled — MKT follows this reading.
- 2:8 τοῦτο: the neuter demonstrative cannot refer to πίστεως (feminine); it points to
  the whole salvation described in vv.5-8, not to faith specifically as a gift.
- 4:8 ἔδωκεν vs LXX ἔλαβες (Ps 68:18): Paul reads "gave" where the LXX has "received" —
  a deliberate application, possibly via targum tradition or homiletical adaptation.
- 4:11 ποιμένας καὶ διδασκάλους: single definite article governs both nouns —
  Granville Sharp rule suggests "pastor-teachers" is one combined office or at minimum
  the closest of all five in function.
- 4:26 ὀργίζεσθε: treated as a concessive imperative ("be angry [if you must]") following
  the LXX of Ps 4:4; not a command to cultivate anger.
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html


EPHESIANS = {
  "1": {
    "1": '<p><strong>ἀπόστολος</strong> (<em>apostolos</em>) carries the legal sense of a commissioned emissary — not self-appointed but sent with delegated authority. The phrase <strong>διὰ θελήματος θεοῦ</strong> (by the will of God) is Paul\'s standard epistolary marker of that commission\'s source. <strong>ἅγιοι</strong> (<em>hagioi</em>, saints) is the corporate designation of the people set apart — the whole community, not an elite. Pairing it with <strong>πιστοί</strong> (<em>pistoi</em>, faithful) indicates both status (set apart) and disposition (trusting).</p>',
    "2": '<p>The pairing <strong>χάρις καὶ εἰρήνη</strong> (grace and peace) is not merely a formal greeting; it fuses the Greek <em>charis</em> (favor bestowed) with the Hebrew <em>shalom</em> (wholeness/well-being), condensing the letter\'s entire argument into the salutation. The double source — <strong>ἀπὸ θεοῦ πατρός... καὶ κυρίου Ἰησοῦ Χριστοῦ</strong> — places God and Christ in coordinate origin, a christological weight that the greeting form quietly carries.</p>',
    "3": '<p>The eulogy opens with a deliberate Greek wordplay: <strong>εὐλογητός</strong> (praised/blessed be) and <strong>εὐλογήσας</strong> (who blessed us) — the same root applied first to God and then to his act toward us. <strong>ἐπουρανίοις</strong> (<em>epouraniois</em>, heavenly realms/places) is a distinctive Ephesian term appearing five times; it designates not a remote location but the sphere of spiritual reality that interpenetrates the present age. <strong>πνευματικῇ εὐλογίᾳ</strong> (spiritual blessing) is comprehensive — every spiritual blessing, not a selection.</p>',
    "4": '<p><strong>ἐξελέξατο</strong> (aorist middle) marks election as a single past act: God chose, at a definite moment (before creation), not as an ongoing process. <strong>πρὸ καταβολῆς κόσμου</strong> (before the foundation of the world) emphasizes pre-temporal divine initiative; the choice precedes existence. <strong>ἁγίους καὶ ἀμώμους</strong> (holy and blameless) echoes the sacrificial vocabulary of Lev 1:3 — the language of the unblemished offering, now applied to those chosen in Christ.</p>',
    "5": '<p><strong>προορίσας</strong> (aorist participle) continues the pre-temporal divine purpose: having predestined. <strong>υἱοθεσία</strong> (<em>huiothesia</em>, adoption as sons/sonship) is a Pauline term drawn from Roman legal practice — formal adoption conferring full legal status as heir. <strong>εὐδοκίαν τοῦ θελήματος αὐτοῦ</strong> (the good pleasure of his will) underlines that the motive is internal to God — not external compulsion or human merit but his own gracious inclination.</p>',
    "6": '<p>The phrase <strong>ἐν τῷ ἠγαπημένῳ</strong> (in the Beloved) is a title — the perfect passive participle used as a proper designation for Christ, parallel to the Father\'s declaration at the baptism. The wordplay <strong>χάριτος... ἐχαρίτωσεν</strong> (grace... graced/freely bestowed) is almost untranslatable: he has graced us with grace. The praise orientation — <strong>εἰς ἔπαινον δόξης</strong> — frames all of 1:3-14 as a doxological movement, not an abstract theological system.</p>',
    "7": '<p><strong>ἀπολύτρωσιν</strong> (<em>apolutrōsin</em>, redemption) is the technical term for ransoming a slave or prisoner. The phrase <strong>διὰ τοῦ αἵματος αὐτοῦ</strong> (through his blood) specifies the redemptive price paid. <strong>παραπτώματα</strong> (transgressions) refers to deliberate sideways steps from the path — distinct from <strong>ἁμαρτία</strong> (missing the mark); Paul\'s usage here stresses volitional departure. Both occur together in 2:1, suggesting he treats them as overlapping categories of human failure.</p>',
    "8": '<p><strong>περισσεύσας</strong> (aorist — he lavished/caused to abound) marks a decisive abundance; God did not dispense grace stingily. <strong>σοφία καὶ φρόνησις</strong> (wisdom and understanding) — the first is the broad capacity for right judgment, the second the practical intelligence to apply it. The lavishing of grace is accompanied by cognitive illumination, not mere forgiveness in isolation.</p>',
    "9": '<p><strong>μυστήριον</strong> (<em>mystērion</em>) does not mean something permanently unknowable; in Paul it is a divine secret formerly hidden but now disclosed — the word is about revelation, not concealment. <strong>κατὰ τὴν εὐδοκίαν αὐτοῦ</strong> (according to his good pleasure) again anchors the disclosure in God\'s internal disposition rather than external pressure. <strong>προέθετο</strong> (purposed/set forth — aorist middle) suggests a plan laid out in advance and now being executed.</p>',
    "10": '<p><strong>ἀνακεφαλαιώσασθαι</strong> (<em>anakephalaiōsasthai</em>) is a compound from <em>kephalē</em> (head) — to recapitulate, to sum up under a single head. The word is used in rhetoric for gathering arguments under a thesis; here it describes the eschatological gathering of all things under Christ as head. <strong>οἰκονομία</strong> (administration/stewardship) frames salvation-history as a managed household economy with appointed times. <strong>πλήρωμα τῶν καιρῶν</strong> (fullness of the times/seasons) — not chronos (clock time) but kairos (appointed moment).</p>',
    "11": '<p><strong>ἐκληρώθημεν</strong> (we were allotted/have obtained an inheritance — passive) reverses the image: not only do we inherit but God allots us as his portion, echoing Deut 32:9 where Israel is the LORD\'s allotted inheritance. <strong>βουλὴ τοῦ θελήματος</strong> (counsel of his will) — the deliberative purpose behind all things. <strong>κατ᾽ ἐνέργειαν</strong> (according to the working) connects purpose to effective operation.</p>',
    "12": '<p><strong>τοὺς προηλπικότας</strong> (perfect active participle — those who had already hoped) likely distinguishes Jewish believers ("we") who had awaited the Messiah from Gentile believers addressed as "you" in v.13. The perfect tense signals a prior, settled hope. <strong>εἰς ἔπαινον δόξης αὐτοῦ</strong> — the third occurrence of this doxological refrain in vv.6,12,14; the threefold repetition structures the entire passage as praise-oriented.</p>',
    "13": '<p><strong>ἐσφραγίσθητε</strong> (you were sealed — aorist passive) marks a decisive past event at conversion. The seal in antiquity marked ownership and authenticity; the Holy Spirit is both the agent and the content of that sealing. <strong>τῷ πνεύματι τῆς ἐπαγγελίας</strong> (the Spirit of the promise — objective genitive) identifies the Spirit as the promised gift long anticipated (Joel 2:28; Isa 44:3). The sequence — heard, believed, sealed — is narrative, not three stages requiring separation in time.</p>',
    "14": '<p><strong>ἀρραβών</strong> (<em>arrhabōn</em>, earnest/deposit) is a commercial term for a down-payment that obligates the giver to pay the remainder. The Spirit is not the whole inheritance but the legally binding pledge of it. <strong>ἀπολύτρωσιν τῆς περιποιήσεως</strong> (redemption of the possession) — the redemption that results in God\'s full possession of his people; or his people coming into full possession of their inheritance. The ambiguity is productive: both senses are present.</p>',
    "15": '<p><strong>ἀκούσας</strong> (aorist participle — after I heard) sets the prayer as a response to news received. The report reached Paul in prison; the Ephesians\' faith in the Lord Jesus and love toward all the saints is the specific occasion for the intercession that follows. No thanksgiving is performative here — it arises from received report.</p>',
    "16": '<p><strong>οὐ παύομαι εὐχαριστῶν</strong> (I do not cease giving thanks — present participle) marks ongoing, unbroken gratitude rather than a single act. <strong>μνείαν ποιούμενος</strong> (making mention — present participle) indicates that the Ephesians are named in Paul\'s ongoing prayer practice. The two participles together describe the texture of intercessory prayer: ceaseless and specific.</p>',
    "17": '<p><strong>πνεῦμα σοφίας καὶ ἀποκαλύψεως</strong> (spirit of wisdom and revelation) — the request is for the Spirit\'s illuminating function, not general wisdom but specifically revelatory wisdom that discloses God. <strong>ἐπιγνώσει</strong> (<em>epignōsei</em>, full/precise knowledge — from <em>epiginōskō</em>) carries an intensified prefix; it is knowing that reaches its object rather than approximate awareness. The knowing sought is knowing <em>him</em> — personal knowledge, not doctrinal catalogue.</p>',
    "18": '<p><strong>πεφωτισμένους τοὺς ὀφθαλμοὺς τῆς καρδίας</strong> (having been enlightened the eyes of your heart — perfect passive participle) — the heart is the faculty of perception and will; Paul asks that its eyes, once enlightened, might see three things: the hope of calling, the riches of inheritance, and the greatness of power (vv.18-19). The genitive <strong>τῆς καρδίας</strong> is idiomatic: the inner eyes of understanding, not literal sight.</p>',
    "19": '<p>Paul stacks four Greek power-words: <strong>δύναμις</strong> (power, inherent capacity), <strong>ἐνέργεια</strong> (working, efficient activity), <strong>κράτος</strong> (dominion, ruling strength), <strong>ἰσχύς</strong> (might, physical force). The accumulation is not redundant; it signals that every mode in which power can be conceived is operative. The phrase <strong>τὸ ὑπερβάλλον μέγεθος</strong> (surpassing greatness) adds a superlative that overflows any single category.</p>',
    "20": '<p><strong>ἐνεργήκεν</strong> (perfect — he wrought/has worked) marks the resurrection as a completed act whose effects persist. <strong>ἐν τοῖς ἐπουρανίοις</strong> (in the heavenly realms — same phrase as v.3) places Christ\'s session in the same sphere as the believers\' blessings; the spatial language is about authority-domain, not geography. <strong>ἐκ νεκρῶν</strong> (out of dead ones — plural) identifies the resurrection as emergence from among the dead, not merely from a state of death.</p>',
    "21": '<p><strong>ὑπεράνω πάσης ἀρχῆς καὶ ἐξουσίας</strong> (far above all rule and authority) — the hierarchical terms derive from Jewish angelology; Paul lists four: <em>archē</em>, <em>exousia</em>, <em>dynamis</em>, <em>kyriōtēs</em>. Christ\'s exaltation supersedes every tier of the cosmic hierarchy whether seen (political) or unseen (angelic). The temporal frame — <strong>οὐ μόνον ἐν τῷ αἰῶνι τούτῳ ἀλλὰ καὶ ἐν τῷ μέλλοντι</strong> — makes the supremacy permanent across both ages.</p>',
    "22": '<p><strong>πάντα ὑπέταξεν ὑπὸ τοὺς πόδας αὐτοῦ</strong> is a citation of Ps 8:6 applied to Christ — the subjection of all things under human feet, fulfilled in the exalted Son of Man. <strong>κεφαλὴν ὑπὲρ πάντα τῇ ἐκκλησίᾳ</strong> (head over all things for/to the church) — the preposition <em>hyper</em> governs two directions simultaneously: he is head over all things and that headship is given <em>for the benefit of</em> the church. The church is not his head but his body — distinct but integral.</p>',
    "23": '<p><strong>τὸ πλήρωμα τοῦ τὰ πάντα ἐν πᾶσιν πληρουμένου</strong> — the participial phrase <em>tou… plēroumenou</em> is ambiguous: middle (he fills all things) or passive (he who is filled). Most interpreters favor the active reading: Christ is the one who fills all in all, and the church as his body is the sphere in which that fullness is expressed. <strong>πλήρωμα</strong> (<em>plērōma</em>) becomes a key term in Ephesians and Colossians; here it carries the sense of completion — what makes something full.</p>'
  },
  "2": {
    "1": '<p><strong>νεκρούς</strong> (dead) is the controlling metaphor of 2:1-10: spiritual death as present condition, not future threat. The dative case <strong>τοῖς παραπτώμασιν καὶ ταῖς ἁμαρτίαις</strong> (in/by trespasses and sins) is instrumental or locative — the sphere or the cause of death. Paul uses both words: <strong>παράπτωμα</strong> (a sideways fall/trespass — deliberate deviation) and <strong>ἁμαρτία</strong> (missing the mark — the broader category). Together they cover the range of human moral failure.</p>',
    "2": '<p><strong>κατὰ τὸν αἰῶνα τοῦ κόσμου τούτου</strong> (according to the age of this world) — two terms for the present fallen order: <em>aiōn</em> (age, temporal frame) and <em>kosmos</em> (world, ordered system). <strong>ἄρχοντα τῆς ἐξουσίας τοῦ ἀέρος</strong> (ruler of the authority of the air) — the aerial domain in first-century cosmology was associated with malevolent spiritual forces. <strong>τοῦ πνεύματος τοῦ νῦν ἐνεργοῦντος</strong> (the spirit now working — present participle) marks present-tense activity, not merely past influence.</p>',
    "3": '<p><strong>σάρξ</strong> (G4561, dispute_level=4) here means the creaturely human nature in its misdirected inclination — not the physical body as evil in itself, but the whole person oriented away from God. <strong>τὰ θελήματα τῆς σαρκός</strong> (the desires of the flesh) and <strong>τῶν διανοιῶν</strong> (of the mind) pair physical impulse with intellectual disposition — both need redemption. <strong>τέκνα φύσει ὀργῆς</strong> (children by nature of wrath) — <em>phusei</em> (by nature) indicates the condition is not merely acquired but constitutional.</p>',
    "4": '<p><strong>ὁ δὲ θεός</strong> (but God) — the adversative marks the theological turning point of the passage. The divine character is specified before the action: <strong>πλούσιος ὢν ἐν ἐλέει</strong> (being rich in mercy — present participle, describing God\'s ongoing character) and <strong>διὰ τὴν πολλὴν ἀγάπην αὐτοῦ</strong> (because of his great love). The reversal of vv.1-3 flows not from human reformation but from God\'s own nature — mercy and love are the sources, not human deserving.</p>',
    "5": '<p><strong>συνεζωοποίησεν</strong> (made alive together with — aorist, compound with <em>syn-</em>) is the first of three <em>syn-</em> compound verbs in vv.5-6 expressing corporate union with Christ. The parenthetical <strong>χάριτί ἐστε σεσωσμένοι</strong> (by grace you are saved — perfect passive periphrastic) disrupts the syntax to insert the theological foundation: salvation as a present state resulting from a past completed act. <strong>ἐστε</strong> (you are) in the present; <strong>σεσωσμένοι</strong> (having been saved) as the standing result.</p>',
    "6": '<p><strong>συνήγειρεν</strong> (raised together — aorist) and <strong>συνεκάθισεν</strong> (seated together — aorist) use the same <em>syn-</em> prefix: believers are co-raised and co-seated with Christ. The session of believers <strong>ἐν τοῖς ἐπουρανίοις</strong> (in the heavenly realms) is presently true — not merely future. The aorist tenses view the action as complete; the present reality is the consequence. This is a realized participation, not merely a promised location.</p>',
    "7": '<p><strong>ἐν τοῖς αἰῶσιν τοῖς ἐπερχομένοις</strong> (in the coming ages — present participle, ongoing sequence) extends the demonstration of grace into the future. <strong>ὑπερβάλλον πλοῦτος τῆς χάριτος</strong> (surpassing riches of grace) — <em>hyperballon</em> appears again (cf. 1:19); the excess of grace exceeds calculation. <strong>χρηστότης</strong> (kindness) specifies the character of grace — not stern magnanimity but warm, active good-will toward the undeserving.</p>',
    "8": '<p><strong>τῇ χάριτί ἐστε σεσωσμένοι διὰ πίστεως</strong> — the perfect periphrastic restated from v.5. The instrument is <strong>πίστεως</strong> (faith — dative of instrument), but the critical point: <strong>τοῦτο οὐκ ἐξ ὑμῶν</strong> (this not from yourselves) — <em>touto</em> is neuter, while <em>pistis</em> (faith) is feminine. The pronoun therefore cannot refer to faith alone; it points to the entire salvation described in vv.5-8. <strong>θεοῦ τὸ δῶρον</strong> (the gift of God — emphatic position) — salvation as the whole is God\'s gift; faith is the means, not the meritorious ground.</p>',
    "9": '<p><strong>οὐκ ἐξ ἔργων</strong> (not from works — emphatic negation) eliminates human achievement as contributing cause. <strong>ἵνα μή τις καυχήσηται</strong> (so that no one might boast — purpose clause with subjunctive) states the design: the exclusion of boasting is a divine goal, not incidental. The construction is purpose, not mere result — God structured salvation to exclude the condition that would generate human pride.</p>',
    "10": '<p><strong>ποίημα</strong> (<em>poiēma</em>, workmanship/work of art) — the word carries the connotation of a crafted object; English "poem" derives from it. God is the craftsman; believers are his creation (second creation in Christ). <strong>κτισθέντες</strong> (created — aorist passive; decisively recreated). <strong>ἐπὶ ἔργοις ἀγαθοῖς</strong> (for good works — purposive) — good works are the purpose of the new creation, not the basis. <strong>προητοίμασεν</strong> (prepared in advance — aorist; God pre-arranged the works) — they walk in a path already laid.</p>',
    "11": '<p><strong>ἀκροβυστία</strong> (uncircumcision) and <strong>περιτομή</strong> (circumcision) — the defining social-religious boundary of the first century. The qualifier <strong>χειροποιήτου</strong> (made by hands) is pointed: it reduces the circumcision to a human physical act, underscoring that the superiority it claimed was itself of human construction. Paul\'s audience is asked to remember this status as past, not as present identity.</p>',
    "12": '<p>Five descriptors of the Gentile condition apart from Christ: without Christ, excluded from citizenship in Israel, strangers to the covenants of promise, without hope, and <strong>ἄθεοι</strong> (<em>atheoi</em>, without God/atheists) in the world. The plural <strong>διαθηκῶν</strong> (covenants — not one covenant but multiple) points to the Abrahamic, Mosaic, Davidic, and new covenant promises collectively. To be a stranger to these is to have no access to their framing of reality.</p>',
    "13": '<p><strong>νυνὶ δέ</strong> (but now — strong temporal contrast) marks the reversal. <strong>ἐν Χριστῷ Ἰησοῦ</strong> (in Christ Jesus — the sphere of the change) and <strong>ἐν τῷ αἵματι τοῦ Χριστοῦ</strong> (by the blood of Christ — the means). <strong>ἐγγύς</strong> (near) draws on Isa 57:19; those who were far have been brought into proximity — not geographical but covenantal. The spatial language (far/near) was standard for Gentile/Jew distinction in Second Temple literature.</p>',
    "14": '<p><strong>αὐτὸς γάρ ἐστιν ἡ εἰρήνη ἡμῶν</strong> (for he himself is our peace — emphatic <em>autos</em>) — Christ does not merely make peace or announce it; he <em>is</em> the peace. <strong>μεσότοιχον τοῦ φραγμοῦ</strong> (middle wall of partition — compound noun, NT hapax <em>mesotoichon</em>) — the dividing wall. Whether this alludes to the Temple soreg (barrier keeping Gentiles from the inner courts) or is purely metaphorical, the image is of a structural barrier demolished.</p>',
    "15": '<p><strong>καταργήσας</strong> (having abolished/rendered inoperative — aorist participle) describes Christ\'s relation to <strong>τὸν νόμον τῶν ἐντολῶν ἐν δόγμασιν</strong> (the law of commandments in ordinances). The focus is on the divisive legal code that enforced the Jew/Gentile boundary, not the entire Mosaic Torah as moral category. <strong>ἕνα καινὸν ἄνθρωπον</strong> (one new humanity/person) — <em>kainos</em> (new in quality, not just temporal novelty) and <em>anthrōpos</em> (human, not <em>anēr</em>/male) — a new corporate humanity created from two.</p>',
    "16": '<p><strong>ἀποκτείνας τὴν ἔχθραν ἐν αὐτῷ</strong> — the enmity is killed in/by <em>him</em> (Christ) or in/by <em>it</em> (the cross). The ambiguity of <em>autō</em> may be productive: Christ on the cross kills the enmity by bearing it. <strong>ἀποκαταλλάξῃ</strong> (reconcile — compound verb with <em>apo-</em> indicating complete or restored reconciliation) — both groups in one body to God. The cross achieves vertical reconciliation (to God) through horizontal unification (Jew and Gentile).</p>',
    "17": '<p><strong>ἐλθὼν εὐηγγελίσατο εἰρήνην</strong> (coming he proclaimed peace — aorist; a completed proclamation) echoes Isa 57:19. The two groups are addressed in reverse order from what might be expected: <strong>ὑμῖν τοῖς μακράν</strong> (to you who were far — the Gentiles addressed first) and <strong>τοῖς ἐγγύς</strong> (to those who were near — Israel). The same Christ preaches peace to both; the message is one.</p>',
    "18": '<p><strong>προσαγωγή</strong> (<em>prosagōgē</em>, access) is a technical term in the ancient world for admission into the presence of royalty or deity — the right of approach. <strong>δι᾽ αὐτοῦ</strong> (through him — the mediatorial route is Christ) and <strong>ἐν ἑνὶ πνεύματι</strong> (in one Spirit — the sphere of approach) make the Trinitarian structure explicit: to the Father, through the Son, in the Spirit. Both groups — <strong>ἀμφότεροι</strong> (both) — share one access, not two separate routes.</p>',
    "19": '<p><strong>οὐκέτι ἐστὲ ξένοι καὶ πάροικοι</strong> (no longer strangers and resident aliens — legal resident alien status without citizenship rights). The contrast terms are <strong>συμπολῖται τῶν ἁγίων</strong> (fellow-citizens with the saints — full civic membership) and <strong>οἰκεῖοι τοῦ θεοῦ</strong> (members of God\'s household — intimate kinship, not merely civic). The movement is from legal alien to citizen to family member — escalating in relational depth.</p>',
    "20": '<p><strong>ἐποικοδομηθέντες</strong> (having been built upon — aorist passive) continues the architectural metaphor. <strong>θεμέλιον τῶν ἀποστόλων καὶ προφητῶν</strong> (foundation of the apostles and prophets) — the genitive is appositional: the apostles and prophets <em>are</em> the foundation (not its layers). <strong>ἀκρογωνιαῖος</strong> (<em>akrogōniaios</em>, cornerstone) — debated as foundation cornerstone (binding two walls at the base) or capstone (binding at the top); the building imagery here favors the former: Christ as the determinative stone from which all else is aligned.</p>',
    "21": '<p><strong>πᾶσα οἰκοδομή</strong> — without the article, this may mean "every building" (each local community) rather than "the whole building" (one universal structure). The present participle <strong>αὔξει</strong> (is growing) makes the temple a living, ongoing construction — not a completed monument but a dynamic growth. <strong>εἰς ναὸν ἅγιον</strong> (into a holy temple) — <em>naos</em> is the inner sanctuary, not the outer courts (<em>hieron</em>); the whole community is growing into the most sacred space.</p>',
    "22": '<p><strong>συνοικοδομεῖσθε</strong> (you are being built together — present passive) adds the <em>syn-</em> prefix (together) and addresses the Ephesian community specifically. The ongoing present passive indicates the process is incomplete and God is the builder. <strong>κατοικητήριον τοῦ θεοῦ ἐν πνεύματι</strong> (dwelling place of God in/by the Spirit) — <em>katoikētērion</em> is permanent dwelling (contrast <em>paroikia</em>, sojourning); the Spirit is either the sphere or the agent of this indwelling.</p>'
  },
  "3": {
    "1": '<p><strong>ὁ δέσμιος τοῦ Χριστοῦ Ἰησοῦ</strong> (the prisoner of Christ Jesus) — the genitive is possessive: Paul belongs to Christ in his imprisonment, not merely to Caesar. The same designation returns at 4:1. The interruption — Paul begins "for this reason I, Paul…" then digresses through v.13 before completing the sentence at v.14 — is structurally deliberate: the digression explains why the imprisonment is not grounds for discouragement.</p>',
    "2": '<p><strong>οἰκονομίαν τῆς χάριτος</strong> (stewardship/administration of grace — <em>oikonomia</em>) — the household-management term; Paul is the appointed manager of a trust. The grace is not his to generate but to distribute. The phrase <strong>δοθείσης μοι εἰς ὑμᾶς</strong> (given to me for you) marks the directional purpose: the grace-stewardship is apostolically oriented toward the Gentiles.</p>',
    "3": '<p><strong>κατὰ ἀποκάλυψιν</strong> (by/according to revelation) — the knowledge came by divine disclosure, not human investigation. This is consistent with Paul\'s claim in Gal 1:12. <strong>τοῦ μυστηρίου</strong> — the mystery he has written briefly about; the reader is expected to recognize it. <strong>ἐγνωρίσθη</strong> (was made known — aorist passive) positions Paul as recipient, not discoverer.</p>',
    "4": '<p><strong>μυστήριον τοῦ Χριστοῦ</strong> (mystery of Christ — objective genitive: the mystery that concerns/is about Christ) — not a secret teaching Christ possesses but the previously hidden divine plan now disclosed in Christ. Reading (<strong>ἀναγινώσκοντες</strong>, present participle) is assumed to be public, communal — the letter is being read aloud in assembly. The comprehension (<strong>νοῆσαι</strong>, to perceive/understand) is the intended result.</p>',
    "5": '<p><strong>οὐκ ἐγνωρίσθη</strong> (was not made known — aorist passive) establishes a contrast with <strong>νῦν ἀπεκαλύφθη</strong> (now has been revealed — aorist passive). The stress is on the difference between former hiddenness and present disclosure, not absolute ignorance in earlier generations. <strong>ἀποστόλοις καὶ προφήταις</strong> (apostles and prophets — dative of disclosure) — NT apostles and prophets, not the OT prophets, receive the revelation here described.</p>',
    "6": '<p>Three <em>syn-</em> compound nouns, each a NT hapax or near-hapax: <strong>συγκληρονόμα</strong> (co-heirs), <strong>σύσσωμα</strong> (members of the same body — unique compound), <strong>συμμέτοχα</strong> (co-participants/fellow-partakers). The accumulation is literary emphasis through structural parallelism: the Gentiles are fully included, not secondarily attached. All three terms describe the Gentiles in relation to what Israel already had in promise.</p>',
    "7": '<p><strong>κατὰ τὴν ἐνέργειαν τῆς δυνάμεως αὐτοῦ</strong> (according to the working of his power) — the same phrase as in 1:19. The grace given for the ministry is not Paul\'s native capacity but God\'s effective power operating through him. <strong>διάκονος</strong> (servant/minister) is the self-designation — not lord or patron but one who serves at table; the term underscores the subordinate, commissioned character of apostolic ministry.</p>',
    "8": '<p><strong>ἐλαχιστοτέρῳ</strong> (lesser than the least) — a double comparative grammatically irregular and deliberately excessive: the comparative of the superlative <em>elachistos</em>. Paul names himself beneath even the category of "least." <strong>τοῖς ἔθνεσιν εὐαγγελίσασθαι τὸν ἀνεξιχνίαστον πλοῦτον τοῦ Χριστοῦ</strong> — <strong>ἀνεξιχνίαστον</strong> (unsearchable/untraceable — beyond investigation by following the tracks) positions the riches of Christ as inexhaustible and beyond calculation.</p>',
    "9": '<p><strong>φωτίσαι</strong> (to illuminate/enlighten — aorist infinitive of purpose) — the second purpose of Paul\'s ministry: making visible what was hidden. <strong>ἀποκεκρυμμένου</strong> (having been hidden — perfect passive participle) marks the hiddenness as a completed prior state now overcome. <strong>τοῦ θεοῦ τοῦ τὰ πάντα κτίσαντος</strong> (of God who created all things) — the creator of all things is the same one who hid and now discloses the mystery; creation and redemption share one agent.</p>',
    "10": '<p><strong>πολυποίκιλος σοφία</strong> (manifold/many-colored wisdom — <em>polypoikilos</em> is NT hapax) — the adjective is applied in classical sources to embroidered cloth with many patterns; God\'s wisdom displayed through the church is variegated, not monochrome. <strong>ταῖς ἀρχαῖς καὶ ταῖς ἐξουσίαις</strong> (to the rulers and authorities in the heavenly realms) — the church is the instrument by which angelic/cosmic powers are shown God\'s wisdom. The church\'s existence is itself a cosmic announcement.</p>',
    "11": '<p><strong>κατὰ πρόθεσιν τῶν αἰώνων</strong> (according to the purpose of the ages — literally "the eternal purpose") — <em>aiōnōn</em> (of the ages) functions as an intensive genitive expressing permanence; God\'s purpose spans and transcends all ages. <strong>ἐν τῷ Χριστῷ Ἰησοῦ τῷ κυρίῳ ἡμῶν</strong> — the full title marks the sentence\'s doxological weight; the eternal purpose is located in, and accomplished in, this specific person.</p>',
    "12": '<p><strong>παρρησίαν καὶ προσαγωγήν</strong> (boldness and access) — the two combined describe the worshipper\'s standing before God. <strong>παρρησία</strong> (<em>parrēsia</em>) in Greek culture meant freedom of speech, the right to speak openly without fear — applied here to prayer. <strong>προσαγωγή</strong> (access, right of approach — same word as 2:18) pairs freedom of speech with the right of entry. Both are <strong>ἐν πεποιθήσει</strong> (with confidence — not anxious or tentative).</p>',
    "13": '<p><strong>αἰτοῦμαι μὴ ἐγκακεῖν</strong> (I ask not to lose heart/faint) — Paul requests that the Ephesians not be discouraged by his sufferings on their behalf. <strong>ἐγκακεῖν</strong> (to faint, grow weary, lose courage — present infinitive) describes a process of giving up. <strong>ἥτις ἐστὶν δόξα ὑμῶν</strong> (which is your glory) — the suffering is reframed not as shame but as honor accruing to them; his chains are a mark of his advocacy for them.</p>',
    "14": '<p><strong>κάμπτω τὰ γόνατά μου</strong> (I bend my knees) — explicit posture of prayer; Jewish practice normally involved standing (1 Kgs 8:22), making kneeling a mark of particular intensity or urgency (Luke 22:41; Acts 20:36). The posture embodies the petition\'s seriousness. The resumption of the interrupted sentence from v.1 signals the prayer is the climax toward which the entire parenthetical section (vv.2-13) pointed.</p>',
    "15": '<p><strong>ἐξ οὗ πᾶσα πατριά</strong> (from whom every family) — the wordplay between <strong>πατριά</strong> (family/clan, from <em>patēr</em>) and <strong>πατήρ</strong> (Father) is deliberate: God the Father is the source from whom all fatherhood and family-identity derives its name. The claim is not merely that God is a father figure but that the very concept of family-naming originates in him — a polemical claim against Roman imperial family ideology.</p>',
    "16": '<p><strong>κατὰ τὸν πλοῦτον τῆς δόξης αὐτοῦ</strong> (according to the riches of his glory) — the measure of the gift is not human need but divine resource. <strong>κραταιωθῆναι</strong> (to be strengthened — aorist passive infinitive) is a strong compound: empowered with might. The target: <strong>εἰς τὸν ἔσω ἄνθρωπον</strong> (into the inner person/man) — the inner self, the willing center, the seat of moral agency (cf. Rom 7:22; 2 Cor 4:16). The Spirit\'s strengthening reaches the deepest interior.</p>',
    "17": '<p><strong>κατοικῆσαι</strong> (<em>katoikēsai</em>, to dwell/settle permanently — aorist infinitive) is contrasted with <em>paroikēsai</em> (to sojourn temporarily). The request is for Christ\'s permanent, not transient, dwelling in the heart — an indwelling that is household-establishment, not a visit. <strong>ἐρριζωμένοι καὶ τεθεμελιωμένοι</strong> (rooted and established — perfect participles) mix botanical and architectural metaphors; both communicate deep, irreversible anchorage in love as the foundation.</p>',
    "18": '<p><strong>τί τὸ πλάτος καὶ μῆκος καὶ ὕψος καὶ βάθος</strong> (what is the breadth and length and height and depth) — four spatial dimensions applied to the love of Christ. The fourfold measure is a conventional device for totality (north, south, east, west; all directions); here it signals that Christ\'s love exceeds any one orientation. The object of comprehension is specified in v.19: the love that surpasses knowledge — a paradox the prayer sustains rather than resolves.</p>',
    "19": '<p><strong>γνῶναι τε τὴν ὑπερβάλλουσαν τῆς γνώσεως ἀγάπην</strong> (to know the love of Christ that surpasses knowledge) — the grammatical structure is intentionally paradoxical: to know the unknowable. <em>Hyperballousa</em> (surpassing — present participle, ongoing excess) marks the love as perpetually beyond the knower\'s grasp even while it is known. <strong>πληρωθῆτε εἰς πᾶν τὸ πλήρωμα τοῦ θεοῦ</strong> (be filled to all the fullness of God) — the passive voice; God is the filler, believers are filled; the corporate "you" (plural) receives the fullness.</p>',
    "20": '<p><strong>ὑπερεκπερισσοῦ</strong> (immeasurably/abundantly beyond — triple-compound superlative, NT hapax) stacks intensifiers: <em>hyper</em> (above) + <em>ek</em> (out of) + <em>perissos</em> (abundant). No English renders it adequately. <strong>κατὰ τὴν δύναμιν τὴν ἐνεργουμένην ἐν ἡμῖν</strong> (according to the power working in us — present passive participle, ongoing) — the criterion for God\'s ability to exceed human imagination is not his abstract omnipotence but the power already actively working within the community.</p>',
    "21": '<p>The doxology closes the first half of Ephesians with matched recipients: <strong>αὐτῷ ἡ δόξα ἐν τῇ ἐκκλησίᾳ καὶ ἐν Χριστῷ Ἰησοῦ</strong> (to him be glory in the church and in Christ Jesus). The church and Christ are the twin spheres of divine glory-display — the heavenly and the embodied. <strong>εἰς πάσας τὰς γενεὰς τοῦ αἰῶνος τῶν αἰώνων</strong> (to all the generations of the age of ages) — a heaping of temporal expressions for eternity. <strong>Ἀμήν</strong> seals the doxology as community affirmation.</p>'
  },
  "4": {
    "1": '<p><strong>παρακαλῶ</strong> (I urge/beseech — present indicative) is the characteristic Pauline transition from indicative to imperative: because of the doctrinal foundation (chs.1-3), here is how to live. The tone is exhortation, not command — the same verb used for comfort and consolation. <strong>ἀξίως τῆς κλήσεως</strong> (worthily of the calling) — the calling established in 1:4-14; the conduct must correspond to the identity. <strong>δέσμιος ἐν κυρίῳ</strong> (prisoner in the Lord — same phrase as 3:1) — Paul\'s imprisonment lends moral authority to the exhortation.</p>',
    "2": '<p><strong>ταπεινοφροσύνη</strong> (lowliness of mind/humility) — in Greco-Roman ethics this term was often pejorative (servility); Paul revalues it as a virtue essential to community. <strong>πραΰτης</strong> (meekness/gentleness — strength under control) and <strong>μακροθυμία</strong> (longsuffering — the long-tempered disposition that bears provocation without retaliation). <strong>ἀνεχόμενοι ἀλλήλων</strong> (bearing with one another — present participle, continuous) — the ongoing practice of tolerating friction within the body.</p>',
    "3": '<p><strong>σπουδάζοντες</strong> (making every effort/haste — present participle; urgency) — unity is not automatic; it requires diligent effort. <strong>τηρεῖν τὴν ἑνότητα τοῦ πνεύματος</strong> (to keep the unity of the Spirit) — the unity is already given by the Spirit (one body, one Spirit); the task is preservation, not creation. <strong>ἐν τῷ συνδέσμῳ τῆς εἰρήνης</strong> (in the bond of peace) — peace is the ligament that holds the unity together.</p>',
    "4": '<p>The seven-fold unity formula begins: <strong>ἓν σῶμα καὶ ἓν πνεῦμα</strong> (one body, one Spirit) — the body is the church, the Spirit is the animating principle. <strong>μία ἐλπίς</strong> (one hope) — the eschatological common destiny shared by all members. The abruption in Greek — no verb "there is" — creates a staccato confessional rhythm, almost creedal. Each "one" carries its own weight.</p>',
    "5": '<p><strong>εἷς κύριος, μία πίστις, ἓν βάπτισμα</strong> — the second triad. <strong>κύριος</strong> (Lord) — the confessional title of Jesus (Phil 2:11; Rom 10:9). <strong>πίστις</strong> (faith) here likely refers to the content of belief (the one faith, the body of trust), not merely the act of trusting. <strong>βάπτισμα</strong> (baptism) — the one initiatory rite shared by all, Jewish and Gentile alike, in contrast to the divisive rite of circumcision recalled in 2:11.</p>',
    "6": '<p><strong>εἷς θεός καὶ πατήρ πάντων</strong> (one God and Father of all) — the third triad reaches its apex in the Shema-echoing monotheism. Three prepositional phrases qualify the one God: <strong>ὁ ἐπὶ πάντων</strong> (over all — sovereignty), <strong>καὶ διὰ πάντων</strong> (through all — agency), <strong>καὶ ἐν πᾶσιν</strong> (in all — immanence). The prepositional variation prevents any single relation from exhausting the divine presence.</p>',
    "7": '<p><strong>ἑκάστῳ δὲ ἡμῶν</strong> (but to each one of us — emphatic distribution) pivots from the sevenfold unity to diversity within it. <strong>κατὰ τὸ μέτρον τῆς δωρεᾶς τοῦ Χριστοῦ</strong> (according to the measure of the gift of Christ) — Christ is both the giver and the standard of the gift. The measure is his sovereign apportionment, not human election or merit.</p>',
    "8": '<p><strong>διὸ λέγει</strong> (therefore it says — introducing Ps 68:18 [LXX 67:19]) — the citation is introduced without naming the Psalm; the congregation is expected to recognize it. Critically, Paul reads <strong>ἔδωκεν δόματα τοῖς ἀνθρώποις</strong> (gave gifts to men) where the LXX has "received gifts among men." This deliberate adaptation — gave rather than received — applies the Psalm to the exalted Christ distributing gifts to the church. The ascent/giving logic depends on this reading.</p>',
    "9": '<p><strong>τὸ δὲ ἀνέβη</strong> (the "he ascended") — Paul interprets the Psalm\'s "ascent" by inferring a prior descent. The parenthetical argument is: ascent presupposes prior descent; Christ\'s exaltation presupposes his incarnation/descent. <strong>εἰς τὰ κατώτερα μέρη τῆς γῆς</strong> (into the lower parts of the earth) — interpreted as the incarnation (earth is lower than heaven) or as death/Hades; the former fits better here since the contrast is ascension above all heavens.</p>',
    "10": '<p><strong>ὁ καταβάς αὐτός ἐστιν καὶ ὁ ἀναβάς</strong> (the one who descended is himself also the one who ascended) — the same person traverses the full cosmic range: incarnation to exaltation. <strong>ὑπεράνω πάντων τῶν οὐρανῶν</strong> (far above all the heavens) — in Jewish cosmology there were multiple heavens (2 Cor 12:2 mentions a third); Christ\'s ascent surpasses them all. The purpose: <strong>ἵνα πληρώσῃ τὰ πάντα</strong> (in order that he might fill all things) — same <em>plēroō</em> root as 1:23; the filling is cosmic in scope.</p>',
    "11": '<p><strong>αὐτὸς ἔδωκεν</strong> (he himself gave — emphatic; Christ is the direct giver of the ministries) — five gifts to the church: <strong>ἀποστόλους</strong> (apostles), <strong>προφήτας</strong> (prophets), <strong>εὐαγγελιστάς</strong> (evangelists), <strong>ποιμένας καὶ διδασκάλους</strong> (pastors and teachers). The last pair shares a single definite article, possibly indicating a combined role — the pastor who teaches — or at minimum the closest functional overlap of all five.</p>',
    "12": '<p>Three purpose clauses with <strong>πρός / εἰς / εἰς</strong>: <strong>πρὸς τὸν καταρτισμόν</strong> (for the equipping — <em>katartismos</em>, the outfitting of soldiers or the setting of a bone; restoring to proper function), <strong>εἰς ἔργον διακονίας</strong> (for works of service/ministry), <strong>εἰς οἰκοδομὴν τοῦ σώματος</strong> (for the building up of the body of Christ). The direction is outward: the gifted ministries equip the whole people for ministry, which builds the body.</p>',
    "13": '<p><strong>εἰς τὴν ἑνότητα τῆς πίστεως</strong> (to the unity of the faith) — the telos of the ministry gifts. <strong>ἄνδρα τέλειον</strong> (mature/perfect man) — <em>anēr</em> here is used corporately (not gender-specifically) for the full-grown humanity constituted by the community; the mature community is the "one new humanity" of 2:15 now fully realized. <strong>μέτρον ἡλικίας τοῦ πληρώματος τοῦ Χριστοῦ</strong> (measure of the fullness/stature of Christ) — <em>plēroma</em> again; Christ\'s fullness is the standard of maturity.</p>',
    "14": '<p><strong>νήπιοι</strong> (infants — here pejoratively: immature, dependent, easily destabilized). <strong>κλυδωνιζόμενοι</strong> (tossed by waves) and <strong>περιφερόμενοι</strong> (carried about) — both present passive participles depicting continuous instability. <strong>κυβεία</strong> (sleight of dice — <em>kubeia</em>, from <em>kubos</em>, dice) applies the image of cheating at dice to doctrinal manipulation; the deceitful methods (<strong>μεθοδεία</strong>) of error are deliberate and structured, not random.</p>',
    "15": '<p><strong>ἀληθεύοντες ἐν ἀγάπῃ</strong> (speaking/living the truth in love — present participle; ongoing practice) — <em>alētheuō</em> is broader than speech: holding and enacting truth. The contrast with the deception of v.14 is sharp. <strong>αὐξήσωμεν εἰς αὐτόν τὰ πάντα</strong> (we may grow into him in all things — he is the direction of growth, not merely its cause): Christ as the head toward whom the body grows, not merely from whom it grows.</p>',
    "16": '<p><strong>ἐξ οὗ πᾶν τὸ σῶμα</strong> (from whom the whole body) — Christ the head is the origin and organizing principle. <strong>συναρμολογούμενον καὶ συμβιβαζόμενον</strong> (joined together and held together — present passive participles) — two architectural/anatomical compound verbs; the body has structure (fitted) and integrity (compacted). <strong>διὰ πάσης ἁφῆς τῆς ἐπιχορηγίας</strong> (through every supporting ligament) — the connective tissue metaphor; each part has a defined supply function that supports the whole.</p>',
    "17": '<p><strong>μαρτύρομαι ἐν κυρίῳ</strong> (I testify/solemnly urge in the Lord) — the verb is stronger than <em>parakaleō</em>; it carries the weight of an oath-testimony. The contrast with Gentile life (<strong>μηκέτι ὑμᾶς περιπατεῖν καθὼς καὶ τὰ ἔθνη</strong>) is stark: the Ephesian believers must have a fundamentally different manner of life from the surrounding culture. <strong>ματαιότητι τοῦ νοός</strong> (futility/vanity of the mind) — the Gentile mind as vain, purposeless, oriented toward nothing.</p>',
    "18": '<p><strong>ἐσκοτωμένοι τῇ διανοίᾳ</strong> (darkened in their understanding — perfect passive participle, settled state). <strong>ἀπηλλοτριωμένοι τῆς ζωῆς τοῦ θεοῦ</strong> (alienated from the life of God — same verb as 2:12; estrangement is the result). The cause: <strong>διὰ τὴν ἄγνοιαν τὴν οὖσαν ἐν αὐτοῖς</strong> (through the ignorance that is in them) and <strong>διὰ τὴν πώρωσιν τῆς καρδίας αὐτῶν</strong> (through the hardening of their heart — <em>pōrōsis</em>, a medical term for the calcification of bone or cartilage; a hardened organ that cannot receive).</p>',
    "19": '<p><strong>ἀπηλγηκότες</strong> (having become callous/past feeling — perfect active participle; a condition arrived at and now settled). The word means to cease feeling pain — moral anesthesia. <strong>ἀσελγείᾳ</strong> (sensuality/licentiousness) — the abandonment of social restraint; the word connotes not merely private immorality but public shamelessness. <strong>πλεονεξία</strong> (greed — always wanting more) pairs with sensuality as the twin engines of this descent.</p>',
    "20": '<p><strong>ὑμεῖς δὲ οὐχ οὕτως ἐμάθετε τὸν Χριστόν</strong> (but you did not learn Christ in this way — emphatic pronoun <em>hymeis de</em>) — the emphatic contrast sets the Ephesian community decisively apart from the Gentile pattern just described. <strong>ἐμάθετε τὸν Χριστόν</strong> (learned Christ) — an unusual construction; not "learned about Christ" but "learned Christ" — personal encounter with him as the content of the learning.</p>',
    "21": '<p><strong>εἴγε αὐτὸν ἠκούσατε καὶ ἐν αὐτῷ ἐδιδάχθητε</strong> (if indeed you heard him and were taught in him) — the conditional is not doubt but affirmation; the two aorists (heard, were taught) describe the once-for-all catechetical formation. <strong>καθώς ἐστιν ἀλήθεια ἐν τῷ Ἰησοῦ</strong> (as truth is in Jesus) — the unusual use of <em>Iēsou</em> (the human name alone) grounds truth in the historical particularity of the incarnate person, not abstract doctrine.</p>',
    "22": '<p><strong>ἀποθέσθαι ὑμᾶς κατὰ τὴν προτέραν ἀναστροφήν</strong> (to put off, concerning your former way of life — aorist infinitive, decisive act) — the putting off is a single decisive act, like removing a garment. <strong>τὸν παλαιὸν ἄνθρωπον</strong> (the old man/humanity) is the corporate old self in Adam. <strong>φθειρόμενον κατὰ τὰς ἐπιθυμίας τῆς ἀπάτης</strong> (being corrupted by the desires of deceit — present passive participle; the old humanity is in the process of ongoing decay).</p>',
    "23": '<p><strong>ἀνανεοῦσθαι δὲ τῷ πνεύματι τοῦ νοός ὑμῶν</strong> (to be renewed in the spirit of your mind — present passive infinitive, ongoing process) — the middle term between putting off the old (v.22, aorist) and putting on the new (v.24, aorist). Renewal is continuous. <strong>πνεύματι τοῦ νοός</strong> (spirit of the mind) is a distinctive genitive — the animating principle or disposition of the mind; it may echo the pneuma/nous distinction in contemporary philosophy, here united rather than opposed.</p>',
    "24": '<p><strong>ἐνδύσασθαι τὸν καινὸν ἄνθρωπον</strong> (to put on the new humanity — aorist, decisive action). <strong>καινός</strong> (new in quality, not merely recent — contrast <em>neos</em>) — the new humanity is qualitatively different, not just temporally new. <strong>κατὰ θεὸν κτισθέντα</strong> (created according to God — cf. 2:10; the new self is a divine creation, not human self-improvement). <strong>ἐν δικαιοσύνῃ καὶ ὁσιότητι τῆς ἀληθείας</strong> (in righteousness and holiness of truth) — <em>dikaiosynē</em> (righteous character toward others) and <em>hosiotēs</em> (holiness/piety toward God) as the twin dimensions of the new life.</p>',
    "25": '<p><strong>ἀποθέμενοι τὸ ψεῦδος</strong> (having put off falsehood — aorist participle; the decisive removal that precedes what follows) and <strong>λαλεῖτε ἀλήθειαν</strong> (speak truth — present imperative, ongoing). The specific ground: <strong>ὅτι ἐσμὲν ἀλλήλων μέλη</strong> (because we are members of one another). Honesty is not merely ethical but ecclesiological — lying to a fellow member is a form of self-harm to the body.</p>',
    "26": '<p><strong>ὀργίζεσθε καὶ μὴ ἁμαρτάνετε</strong> (be angry and do not sin) — a quotation of Ps 4:4 LXX. The construction is best read as concessive imperative: "if you are angry, do not sin" or "even if anger comes, do not let it lead to sin." Paul is not commanding anger but acknowledging its reality and limiting its damage. <strong>ὁ ἥλιος μὴ ἐπιδυέτω</strong> (let not the sun go down — prohibitive imperative) sets an urgency: anger resolved daily, not nursed into settled hostility.</p>',
    "27": '<p><strong>μηδὲ δίδοτε τόπον τῷ διαβόλῳ</strong> (and give no place/foothold to the devil — present imperative prohibition) — <em>topos</em> (place) can be a spatial location, a legal opportunity, or a beachhead. Unresolved anger creates an opening (<em>topos</em>) that becomes an exploitable position. The connection between anger management and spiritual warfare is not incidental; Paul treats them as directly linked.</p>',
    "28": '<p><strong>ὁ κλέπτων μηκέτι κλεπτέτω</strong> (the one who steals, let him steal no more — present participle and present imperative; the thief is characterized by his ongoing habit, and the command ends it). <strong>κοπιάτω ἐργαζόμενος τὸ ἀγαθόν</strong> (let him labor, working the good — present participle emphasizing the ongoing character of legitimate work). The purpose of honest labor: <strong>ἵνα ἔχῃ μεταδιδόναι</strong> (in order that he might have something to share) — work is oriented not toward accumulation but redistribution.</p>',
    "29": '<p><strong>λόγος σαπρός</strong> (rotten/corrupt word — <em>sapros</em> is used of rotten fruit and fish) — speech that is decayed, worthless. The alternative: <strong>εἴ τις ἀγαθὸς πρὸς οἰκοδομήν</strong> (whatever is good for building up — <em>oikodomē</em>, same word as the body-building in vv.12,16) — speech is either demolition or construction. <strong>κατὰ τὴν χρείαν</strong> (according to the need) — the criterion is the hearer\'s specific situation, not the speaker\'s self-expression.</p>',
    "30": '<p><strong>μὴ λυπεῖτε τὸ πνεῦμα τὸ ἅγιον</strong> (do not grieve the Holy Spirit — present imperative prohibition; stop or do not start grieving) — the Spirit is a person who can be grieved; the prohibition implies relational damage. The ground clause: <strong>ἐν ᾧ ἐσφραγίσθητε</strong> (in whom you were sealed — aorist passive, same verb as 1:13) — the sealing is the basis for the appeal; to grieve the Spirit is to damage the relationship that guarantees the inheritance.</p>',
    "31": '<p>Six terms for the corrosive interior and its expression: <strong>πικρία</strong> (bitterness — the root; the settled inner disposition of resentment), <strong>θυμός</strong> (passion/rage — sudden explosion of anger), <strong>ὀργή</strong> (anger — settled, burning anger), <strong>κραυγή</strong> (outcry/clamor — the vocal expression), <strong>βλασφημία</strong> (slander/abusive speech), and <strong>κακία</strong> (malice — the comprehensive term for wickedness). The list moves from interior attitude through verbal expression to general disposition.</p>',
    "32": '<p><strong>χαριζόμενοι ἑαυτοῖς</strong> (forgiving one another — present participle; ongoing practice; <em>charizomai</em> from <em>charis</em>, grace) — forgiveness is literally grace-giving. The model: <strong>καθὼς καὶ ὁ θεὸς ἐν Χριστῷ ἐχαρίσατο ὑμῖν</strong> (just as God in Christ forgave you — aorist; the divine forgiveness is the completed event that establishes the pattern and the power for human forgiveness). The ethical imperative is grounded in the indicative of divine action.</p>'
  }
}


